<h1 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-Neighborhoods">Neighborhoods</h=
1>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Advanced+Ac=
cess" rel=3D"nofollow">Advanced Access</a></strong>: New technologies to gi=
ve access to immunization data in IIS beyond what is currently offered by H=
L7 v2.&nbsp;</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Auxiliary" =
rel=3D"nofollow">Auxiliary</a></strong>: Additional functions that are not =
central to but may overlap with immunization efforts.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Consumer+Ac=
cess" rel=3D"nofollow">Consumer Access</a></strong>: Providing patients wit=
h immunization information access and control.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Data+Qualit=
y" rel=3D"nofollow">Data Quality</a></strong>: Improving the quality of dat=
a in immunization systems is a continuous process. Crosses over with HL7 v2=
.&nbsp;</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/HL7+V2" rel=
=3D"nofollow">HL7 v2</a></strong>: IIS in the US still transmit the bulk of=
 their data via HL7 v2 VXU and RSP messages. There will continue to be new =
and continuing work in this area.&nbsp;</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Inventory" =
rel=3D"nofollow">Inventory</a></strong>: Improvements to how inventory is t=
racked locally and coordinated with IIS.</p></li>
 <li><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/National" r=
el=3D"nofollow">National</a></strong>: Standards that support CDC efforts t=
o coordinate US immunization activities.&nbsp;</li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Support" re=
l=3D"nofollow">Support</a></strong>: Technologies that could support IIS op=
erations but may or may not be used directly by external systems.&nbsp;</p>=
</li>
 <li>
  <p><strong><a href=3D"https://confluence.hl7.org/display/PHWG/Terminology=
" rel=3D"nofollow">Terminology</a></strong>: Standards that support the dis=
semination and use of coded values such as CVX and NDC.&nbsp;</p></li>
 <li>
  <p style=3D"text-align: left;"><strong>Tertiary Concepts</strong>: Any to=
pic listed here does not represent a standard, but rather are more broad/va=
gue in definition but still have some level of relevance to the IIS world.<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>Other Links</p>
<ul>
 <li><a href=3D"https://www.pewtrusts.org/en/research-and-analysis/reports/=
2024/12/state-public-health-data-reporting-policies-and-practices-vary-wide=
ly" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">State Public Health Data Repor=
ting Policies and Practices Vary Widely</a></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-EmergingStandards:AStructuredAp=
proachtoPublicHealthInteroperability">Emerging Standards: A Structured Appr=
oach to Public Health Interoperability</h1>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-Overview">Overview</h2>
<p>The Emerging Standards (ES) process is designed to identify and develop =
solutions for public health data exchange, focusing on real-world challenge=
s rather than pushing any single technology. The goal is to ensure interope=
rability and efficiency in immunization data exchange by systematically eva=
luating, developing, and advancing new standards while maintaining support =
for existing ones, such as HL7 v2.</p>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-KeyPrinciples">Key Principles</=
h2>
<ul>
 <li data-uuid=3D"21655606-72a2-4774-b3a2-c3a5c5a1e0bb"><strong>Problem-Sol=
ving, Not Just Technology Adoption</strong>: The implementation of FHIR or =
any other standard is not an end goal but a potential solution to specific =
challenges in public health data exchange.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"6cff1fe0-4a29-4a51-830a-0c7aef6319ea"><strong>Active Part=
icipation in Standard Development</strong>: The FHIR community does not hav=
e deep expertise in immunizations; therefore, we must engage in its develop=
ment to ensure public health needs are addressed.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"53830b06-404f-4a52-a11a-506a9b4a796b"><strong>Standards a=
s a Framework, Not a Ready-Made Solution</strong>: New standards like FHIR =
provide a structure for developing solutions but do not come pre-built. Pub=
lic health organizations must tailor these frameworks to their specific nee=
ds.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"d8e5fff1-0f9e-401a-917d-98c6aa6d5b4d"><strong>Multiple Im=
plementation Guides (IGs) for Specific Use Cases</strong>: There will not b=
e a single IG, but rather a collection of IGs addressing various use cases =
at different maturity levels.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"2be4925b-5284-4da0-b42e-1b480a9f6aeb"><strong>Collaborati=
on and Coalition-Building</strong>: Emerging standards require partnerships=
 across multiple organizations to ensure widespread adoption and sustainabi=
lity.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-TheSeven-StageEmergingStandards=
Process">The Seven-Stage Emerging Standards Process</h2>
<p>The ES process provides a structured approach to standard development, e=
nsuring ideas mature properly before becoming national or global standards.=
 The stages are:</p>
<ul>
 <li data-uuid=3D"1e264f5e-cd26-4fae-8783-78eddd8c1ab6"><strong>Idea</stron=
g>: A concept is identified for potential standardization.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"4ab6785d-13f3-4150-b13e-9c40505cd10e"><strong>Monitor</st=
rong>: The idea is tracked, and background information is gathered.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"7fe00811-5bba-4f67-b120-cbd894892359"><strong>Gather</str=
ong>: Stakeholder input and feasibility assessments refine the idea.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"8f6ee3b5-36c0-4a3f-9ed9-ef43529927e9"><strong>Start</stro=
ng>: Initial work begins, such as draft models, demo software, and test cas=
es.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"fce2f004-2715-44c4-a41a-f177234056b1"><strong>Draft</stro=
ng>: Formal documentation and specifications are created, leading to commun=
ity feedback and early implementation.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"772f6aac-1d17-4b07-9d26-78382abd78ba"><strong>Pilot</stro=
ng>: Real-world testing of the standard occurs, allowing for iterative refi=
nement.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"c5bf7548-8313-4284-94ea-8d34437605fc"><strong>Rollout</st=
rong>: The standard is adopted widely, with supporting resources, training,=
 and implementation support.</li>
</ul>
<p>The first four stages (Idea to Start) fall within the <strong>Emerging S=
tandards </strong>framework, where ideas are nurtured. The last three stage=
s (Draft to Rollout) are<strong> Emerged Standards</strong>, which have fun=
ding, dedicated projects, and community engagement.</p>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-SelectingandAdvancingTopics">Se=
lecting and Advancing Topics</h2>
<p>Topics within the Emerging Standards framework come from four primary so=
urces:</p>
<ul>
 <li data-uuid=3D"f5a56554-99c5-4313-bbd6-c6b9e531c1c7"><strong>New Technol=
ogies</strong>: Innovations such as FHIR subscriptions that could benefit i=
mmunization data exchange.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"3c07cfbe-6547-43df-919f-912619a4a26b"><strong>Funder Prio=
rities</strong>: Areas identified as high-priority by organizations like CD=
C or other national partners.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"094b11c1-9b0b-4686-92bd-606308172f63"><strong>Community N=
eeds</strong>: Issues raised by IIS, public health agencies, and other stak=
eholders.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"c5d12307-6b4d-4fe1-8140-aae36bdb1c59"><strong>Expert Insi=
ghts</strong>: Recommendations from AIRA and HL7 experts based on industry =
trends and emerging needs.</li>
</ul>
<p>The intersection of these sources ensures that the most relevant, feasib=
le, and impactful ideas move forward.</p>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-AMeasuredandStrategicApproach">=
A Measured and Strategic Approach</h2>
<ul>
 <li data-uuid=3D"30f68df4-531d-4a88-828b-ee274295b929"><strong>Time Horizo=
n</strong>: It typically takes at least five years to bring a standard from=
 concept to full implementation. Starting now ensures preparedness for futu=
re needs.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"34b560b0-ea02-4993-a05d-9d10244200da"><strong>Incremental=
 Investment</strong>: Public health resources should be allocated gradually=
, increasing investment as ideas prove viable, preventing wasted efforts on=
 premature national rollouts.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"0eb9df75-06f4-49d3-ae15-9292b77ce367"><strong>Flexible Pr=
ogression</strong>: Ideas can move forward or backward in the process based=
 on evolving priorities, ensuring only well-developed concepts reach implem=
entation.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"8d922346-c19a-470f-b5f8-311804eb2d05"><strong>Graduation =
to Projects</strong>: An idea "graduates" from Emerging Standards when it s=
ecures funding and a committed sponsor to drive full-scale implementation.<=
/li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"EmergingStandardsforImmunizations-TheValueofEmergingStandards">Th=
e Value of Emerging Standards</h2>
<p>Without a structured approach, promising ideas may either be forgotten o=
r rushed into implementation without adequate preparation. The ES framework=
 ensures:</p>
<ul>
 <li data-uuid=3D"24629e7c-7a75-41bb-8fbe-d3f03cde6987"><strong>A pipeline =
of shovel-ready projects</strong> that can be rapidly advanced when funding=
 becomes available.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"45a0599c-afc5-4539-9c1f-57104d559ef0"><strong>A transpare=
nt, systematic approach</strong> that prevents rushed or reactionary decisi=
on-making.</li>
 <li data-uuid=3D"c16687fe-9d7d-4fc1-925f-f4f51400d08d"><strong>A community=
-driven model</strong> where ideas are vetted collaboratively rather than d=
ictated from the top down.</li>
</ul>
<p>By fostering thoughtful development, engaging key stakeholders, and bala=
ncing stability with innovation, the Emerging Standards process ensures tha=
t public health remains at the forefront of data interoperability, ready to=
 meet both current and future challenges.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
